00:04:08,720 --> 00:04:13,840
The most fundamental concept in our today's discussion is the notion of a probability

43
00:04:13,840 --> 00:04:19,040
distribution. In general, we deal with an abstract set of possible states,

44
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:26,960
and to each of those states, we assign a positive number between 0 and 1. This number

45
00:04:26,960 --> 00:04:32,800
reflects our degree of belief in how likely that particular state is to occur.

46
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:38,800
You're probably familiar with thinking about probability in terms of the proportion of

47
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:45,280
outcomes from high school. For example, a six-sided die has six possible states.

48
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:52,560
To find the probability of rolling a three, for example, you would roll the die many times,

49
00:04:53,200 --> 00:04:59,200
count how often it lands on three, and divide it by the total number of rolls.

50
00:05:00,160 --> 00:05:06,000
As you increase the number of rolls, this ratio converges to 1 over 6,

51
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,440
which is the probability for any side of a fair die.

52
00:05:10,480 --> 00:05:15,600
This approach, which relies on repeated trials and tracking outcomes,

53
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:19,200
is called the frequentist interpretation of probability.

54
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:25,760
While this interpretation works well for dice or coin flips, it has limitations.

55
00:05:26,560 --> 00:05:32,640
Consider a weather forecast stating the probability of rain tomorrow is 70%.

56
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:39,120
We intuitively understand this, but it doesn't fit neatly into the frequentist definition.

57
00:05:39,920 --> 00:05:46,960
We can't repeat tomorrow's weather multiple times to find the frequency of rain outcomes.

58
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:51,120
Tomorrow will happen only once, and it will either rain or not.

59
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:54,720
This is why we'll adopt the Bayesian view,

60
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:59,280
which treats probability more generally as the degree of belief.

61
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:08,880
When we say rain with probability 0.7, it means we've assigned a 0.7 degree of certainty to it.

62
00:06:10,080 --> 00:06:15,120
While this definition might seem very broad, it still obeys certain laws.

63
00:06:15,840 --> 00:06:22,400
The most crucial one is that all the degrees of belief you assign to possible states

64
00:06:22,400 --> 00:06:24,080
must sum to 1.

65
00:06:24,080 --> 00:06:28,560
For instance, if there are only two outcomes, rain and sun,

66
00:06:28,560 --> 00:06:36,400
then saying the probability of rain is 0.7 implies that the probability of sun is 0.3.

67
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:40,560
This brings us to the notion of a probability distribution.

68
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:48,080
Essentially, it is a function that maps each possible state to its assigned probability value.

69
00:06:48,080 --> 00:06:50,880
Because probabilities must sum to 1,

70
00:06:50,880 --> 00:06:55,680
we can't manipulate this function for one state independently of others.

71
00:06:56,240 --> 00:06:58,960
It characterizes the system as a whole,

72
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:04,160
completely describing how uncertainty is distributed among individual states.

73
00:07:05,040 --> 00:07:08,720
Here are a few examples of probability distributions.

74
00:07:08,720 --> 00:07:14,960
For a fair die, the distribution is uniform, each side has a possibility of 1 over 6.

75
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:18,880
The distribution of heights of adults in a population

76
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:23,040
follows the famous bell-shaped Gaussian distribution.

77
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:25,520
There is a technical detail here.

78
00:07:25,520 --> 00:07:32,160
Since height is a continuous variable, the probability distribution must integrate to 1,

79
00:07:32,160 --> 00:07:35,840
meaning that the area under the entire curve equals to 1.

80
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:39,520
But this is just a general case of summation.

81
00:07:39,520 --> 00:07:44,720
You can think of continuous distributions as being made up of a large number of tiny,

82
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:46,160
discrete bins.

83
00:07:46,160 --> 00:07:48,800
It won't change the core concepts we are discussing.

84
00:07:49,600 --> 00:07:54,000
So far, we've only looked at the probability distributions over states

85
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,120
that can be neatly arranged on a one-dimensional line.

86
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:03,920
But what about more complex scenarios, like states that include both height and weight?

87
00:08:04,880 --> 00:08:09,520
We could try to put them on a one-dimensional line, but that's not very enlightening.

88
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:16,880
Instead, it is more natural to think of states as occupying a two-dimensional plane

89
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:19,760
with one coordinate for the height and one for the weight.

90
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:25,280
Then, each point on this plane corresponds to a particular state,

91
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:31,200
and we can represent its probability with color or as a third coordinate.

92
00:08:32,160 --> 00:08:37,280
For more coordinates, we can't directly visualize higher dimensions,

93
00:08:37,280 --> 00:08:39,040
but the idea remains the same.

94
00:08:39,760 --> 00:08:44,880
In machine learning, we often deal with much higher-dimensional probability distributions.

95
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:49,440
For instance, all possible 100x100 pixel images

96
00:08:50,080 --> 00:08:55,920
occupy a 10,000-dimensional space with one axis for each pixel's value.

97
00:08:56,640 --> 00:09:00,640
We can then reason about the probability distribution of images

98
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:05,040
by assigning a probability to each point in this space.

99
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:10,720
But how do we actually use or interact with these complex distributions?

100
00:09:11,520 --> 00:09:15,360
To understand this, let's go back to our simpler example

101
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:21,360
and think about the reverse process of generating outcomes from a probability distribution.

102
00:09:22,080 --> 00:09:25,040
This is called sampling and it is a crucial concept

103
00:09:25,040 --> 00:09:28,640
that is at the heart of many generative AI models.

104
00:09:29,280 --> 00:09:35,600
In the case of a die, rolling it generates a new sample from the underlying distribution,

105
00:09:36,160 --> 00:09:39,280
picking one state at random with a certain probability.

106
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:45,600
Similarly, if we have a way to draw samples from a 10,000-dimensional distribution,

107
00:09:46,480 --> 00:09:48,480
we can generate new images.

108
00:09:49,120 --> 00:09:54,480
Because this distribution captures the structure of data present in natural images,

109
00:09:55,440 --> 00:10:01,920
this would be entirely different from randomly selecting values for each pixel independently,

110
00:10:01,920 --> 00:10:04,240
as this would always result in noise.

111
00:10:05,120 --> 00:10:09,680
Now that we have established a common ground for the language of probability,

112
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:15,600
let's explore the powerful math behind what it takes to describe and model a distribution.

113
00:10:16,880 --> 00:10:19,040
Let's start with the notion of surprise.

114
00:10:20,080 --> 00:10:22,800
Imagine that before you toss a coin,

115
00:10:22,880 --> 00:10:26,320
someone comes up to you and correctly predicts the outcome.

116
00:10:27,520 --> 00:10:30,560
Will you be surprised to see this prediction hold?

117
00:10:31,440 --> 00:10:33,760
Well, maybe, but not too much.

118
00:10:33,760 --> 00:10:36,720
After all, the chance of guessing was 50-50.

119
00:10:37,840 --> 00:10:40,720
Now suppose you do the same for rolling a die

120
00:10:41,280 --> 00:10:45,360
and someone correctly predicts that it would land on 1.

121
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:50,240
You'd likely be more surprised by this rather than a coin, right?

122
00:10:51,120 --> 00:10:54,160
Let's try to formalize this notion of surprise.

123
00:10:55,040 --> 00:10:59,600
Essentially, we're looking for a way to assign a positive number,

124
00:10:59,600 --> 00:11:02,160
a surprizal measure, to each state.

125
00:11:03,120 --> 00:11:09,600
This measure should be a function of probability that gets larger for smaller values

126
00:11:09,600 --> 00:11:12,880
and shrinks to 0 when the probability approaches 1.

127
00:11:14,080 --> 00:11:19,520
After all, events that are guaranteed to happen should have no surprise at all.

128
00:11:20,480 --> 00:11:25,440
A crucial but less obvious aspect is the additive nature of the surprise.

129
00:11:26,320 --> 00:11:31,440
If someone correctly predicts the outcomes of 3 dice rolled simultaneously,

130
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:35,760
we'd be about 3 times as surprised as for 1 die.

131
00:11:36,880 --> 00:11:42,560
But the probability of such an event would be the product of individual die probabilities.

132
00:11:43,600 --> 00:11:49,200
In other words, when probabilities multiply, as for independent events,

133
00:11:49,200 --> 00:11:51,440
the surprizal function should add.

134
00:11:52,720 --> 00:11:58,000
The function that behaves this way is the logarithm of 1 over the probability.

135
00:11:59,120 --> 00:12:00,640
This makes intuitive sense.

136
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:06,400
Surprise is high for rare events and low for common outcomes.

137
00:12:07,520 --> 00:12:10,480
Now that each state has its own surprise,

138
00:12:11,120 --> 00:12:18,000
we can characterize the entire distribution by finding the average surprise packed into it.

139
00:12:18,960 --> 00:12:24,000
This average surprise is what we call the entropy of that distribution.

140
00:12:24,960 --> 00:12:27,840
Mathematically, it is expressed in the following way,

141
00:12:28,640 --> 00:12:31,440
where we sum over all possible states,

142
00:12:32,080 --> 00:12:37,120
multiplying the probability of each state by its surprizal value.

143
00:12:41,120 --> 00:12:47,280
For example, consider a thick coin that lands on heads and tails with probability

144
00:12:47,280 --> 00:12:52,240
49% each and on its side 2% of the time.

145
00:12:53,360 --> 00:12:59,920
If you randomly flip it many times, record your surprizal caused by the outcome of each flip

146
00:13:00,560 --> 00:13:05,120
and compute the average surprizal, what value are you going to get?

147
00:13:06,160 --> 00:13:11,200
Well, every time you get either a heads or a tails, which in total comprises

148
00:13:11,200 --> 00:13:16,240
98% of all the flips, your surprizal is about 0.7.

149
00:13:17,280 --> 00:13:22,160
But in the remaining 2%, your surprizal will be around 4.

150
00:13:22,960 --> 00:13:29,120
So the weighted average given by this formula is approximately equal to 0.8.

151
00:13:30,160 --> 00:13:35,760
Compare this to the entropy of a fair coin that always lands on heads or tails.

152
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:41,520
This value is less, which means you will be on average more surprised

153
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:45,200
by observing outcomes of a coin that lands on its side.

154
00:13:46,080 --> 00:13:50,720
In other words, it has more inherent uncertainty packed into it.

155
00:13:52,720 --> 00:13:55,360
Now, I'd like to highlight an important point.

156
00:13:56,320 --> 00:14:00,720
Computing entropy relies on knowing the probability distribution.

157
00:14:01,680 --> 00:14:05,920
But in real world, when we observe a random variable unfold,

158
00:14:05,920 --> 00:14:10,320
we don't have access to the true underlying probability distribution.

159
00:14:10,960 --> 00:14:14,240
Instead, we usually have an internal model,

160
00:14:14,240 --> 00:14:17,280
what we believe the probability distribution should be.

161
00:14:17,920 --> 00:14:21,040
And this is what we use to assign the probabilities.

162
00:14:22,240 --> 00:14:28,160
The true underlying distribution is hidden and typically far too complex,

163
00:14:28,160 --> 00:14:31,280
so all we have are approximate models of it.

164
00:14:32,400 --> 00:14:34,720
For instance, consider a fair die.

165
00:14:35,520 --> 00:14:40,960
The true probability distribution of its sides slightly deviates from uniform

166
00:14:41,600 --> 00:14:47,680
due to inherent microscopic imperfections in the die itself, air resistance, etc.

167
00:14:48,880 --> 00:14:54,640
It may even include other outcomes, such as landing exactly on a corner

168
00:14:54,640 --> 00:14:59,040
or with vanishingly small probability falling apart in the air.

169
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:07,280
However, we approximate this with a simple uniform distribution, 1 over 6 for each side.

170
00:15:08,160 --> 00:15:12,000
This model captures everything we need for practical purposes.

171
00:15:13,520 --> 00:15:16,880
But what if the deviation between our internal model

172
00:15:16,880 --> 00:15:19,680
and the actual distribution is more drastic?

173
00:15:20,720 --> 00:15:22,080
Let's consider an example.

174
00:15:22,880 --> 00:15:25,520
Suppose someone gives you a coin to flip.

175
00:15:26,480 --> 00:15:29,600
Based on your prior experience with coins,

176
00:15:29,600 --> 00:15:34,720
you believe the probabilities for heads and tails to be around 50% each.

177
00:15:36,080 --> 00:15:40,240
What you don't know though is that this particular coin is rigged,

178
00:15:40,240 --> 00:15:46,640
with its center of mass shifted so that it lands on heads around 99% of the time.

179
00:15:48,160 --> 00:15:52,560
You go ahead and flip it 10 times, getting 10 heads in a row.

180
00:15:53,520 --> 00:15:56,320
Under your current model of a fair coin,

181
00:15:56,880 --> 00:16:02,720
the probability of this happening is extremely small, so you will be very surprised.

182
00:16:03,280 --> 00:16:09,600
However, the actual true probability of this outcome is quite high because the coin is rigged.

183
00:16:10,240 --> 00:16:16,400
Notice that the surprise you experienced is caused by your belief about the probability

184
00:16:16,400 --> 00:16:21,120
distribution being wrong, not because something truly remarkable had happened.

185
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:24,720
This brings us to the idea of cross entropy.

186
00:16:25,520 --> 00:16:33,040
Essentially, it is a function of two probability distributions that quantifies the average surprise

187
00:16:33,040 --> 00:16:39,840
you might expect when observing a random process generated by one probability distribution

188
00:16:40,480 --> 00:16:43,040
while believing it comes from another.

189
00:16:43,920 --> 00:16:51,120
Mathematically, the cross entropy between distributions P, the true one, and Q, your model,

190
00:16:51,680 --> 00:16:59,280
is defined similarly to entropy, but we use P for the outcome probabilities and Q for the

191
00:16:59,280 --> 00:17:05,760
surprizal terms. The surprise given by cross entropy can come from two sources.

192
00:17:06,480 --> 00:17:10,240
The discrepancy between your model and the true distribution,

193
00:17:10,960 --> 00:17:15,840
as well as the inherent uncertainty of the underlying distribution itself.

194
00:17:16,880 --> 00:17:22,400
If P and Q are the same distribution, meaning that you have a perfect model,

195
00:17:22,960 --> 00:17:26,800
the cross entropy is simply equal to the entropy of P.

196
00:17:27,760 --> 00:17:32,000
A key mathematical property, which we're not going to prove rigorously here,

197
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:39,360
is that the cross entropy of distribution P as the ground truth and Q as its model

198
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:46,400
is always greater than or equal to the entropy of P itself. In other words,

199
00:17:46,400 --> 00:17:53,040
believing in their own model of a random variable can only increase the surprise you'll get by

200
00:17:53,040 --> 00:18:00,560
observing it, never decrease it. Another important feature of cross entropy is its asymmetry.

201
00:18:01,360 --> 00:18:07,360
The roles of P and Q matter and swapping them can lead to very different results.

202
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:15,200
Let's explore this with two examples. First, believing a coin is fair when it is actually

203
00:18:15,200 --> 00:18:24,480
rigged. Suppose the true distribution P is a rigged coin, 99% for heads, 1% for tails.

204
00:18:25,200 --> 00:18:32,400
But your model Q is a fair coin. For a single flip, the cross entropy can be calculated in

205
00:18:32,400 --> 00:18:41,120
the following way and is equal to approximately 0.7. Now let's reverse the scenario. What if you

206
00:18:41,120 --> 00:18:50,000
believe a coin is rigged when it is actually fair? Computing the cross entropy gives us 2.3. This

207
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:57,520
value is much larger than the other way around. This is because half the time when you see tails,

208
00:18:57,600 --> 00:19:03,200
you will be extremely surprised as your model predicted this was very unlikely.

209
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:10,960
The other half of the time when you see heads, you'll have a very low surprise. But the extreme

210
00:19:10,960 --> 00:19:17,760
surprise from tails dominates, leading to a high average surprise measured by the cross entropy.

211
00:19:19,600 --> 00:19:25,680
Our examples of cross entropy highlight an important question. How can we quantify the

212
00:19:25,680 --> 00:19:32,240
difference between our model's beliefs and the reality? Can we somehow isolate the part of the

213
00:19:32,240 --> 00:19:38,480
surprise that comes purely from our model's inaccuracy, rather than from the inherent

214
00:19:38,480 --> 00:19:44,080
uncertainty in the data? This is where the concept of Kullback-Liebler divergence,

215
00:19:44,080 --> 00:19:50,880
or KL divergence for short, comes into play. It allows us to peel away layers of surprise.

216
00:19:51,840 --> 00:19:58,240
Recall our definition of cross entropy. This measures the total surprise when using Q to

217
00:19:58,240 --> 00:20:06,000
predict P. Now, what if we subtracted the entropy of P from this? This formula represents the

218
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:13,280
inherent uncertainty in P itself. By subtracting it from the cross entropy and using the properties

219
00:20:13,360 --> 00:20:22,080
of logarithms, we are left with this. This is the KL divergence. It measures the extra surprise

220
00:20:22,080 --> 00:20:28,640
we get from using Q as our model instead of P, beyond the surprise inherent in P.

221
00:20:30,080 --> 00:20:36,960
In our coin analogy, it is like isolating the surprise caused by believing in the wrong model,

222
00:20:36,960 --> 00:20:40,320
separate from the surprise caused by the coin flip itself.

223
00:20:41,360 --> 00:20:45,120
But why might we need to measure this discrepancy in the first place?

224
